From: knaff@imag.fr (Alain Knaff)
Subject: Re: MS-DOS filesystem options are not passed
Date: 29 Nov 1993 12:00:07 GMT

In <MUTS.93Nov28144204@compi.hobby.nl> Peter Mutsaers writes
>somehow I am not able to pass options to the MS-DOS filesystem. I
>specify them in fstab or with the -o option to mount, but in function
>parse_options() in ./fs/msdos/inode.c the options argument always is
>empty.
>
>I think to remember that some patchlevels ago of the kernel I could
>pass options to the MS-DOS filesystem.
>
>Does anyone know what is wrong or if the whole support for options was
>removed?
>
>Thanks,

 The bug is not in the kernel, but in the /etc/mount program: it does
not propagate filesystem specific options ("extra options") to the 
kernel.

Here is a patch (against the mount of the utile-2.1 package):

*** mount.c.orig        Sat Oct  9 14:45:51 1993
--- mount.c     Thu Oct 28 17:59:41 1993
***************
*** 102,129 ****
--- 102,132 ----
  static inline void
  parse_opt (const char *opt, int *mask, char *extra_opts)
  {
    const struct opt_map *om;
  
    for (om = opt_map; om->opt != NULL; ++om)
      if (streq (opt, om->opt))
        {
        if (om->inv)
          *mask &= ~om->mask;
        else
          *mask |= om->mask;
        return;
        }
+   if ( *extra_opts )
+     strcat( extra_opts, "," );
+   strcat( extra_opts, opt );
  }
    
  /* Take -o options list and compute 4th and 5th args to mount(2).  flags
     gets the standard options and extra_opts anything we don't recognize.  */
  static void
  parse_opts (char *opts, int *flags, char **extra_opts)
  {
    char *opt;
  
    if (opts != NULL)
      {
        *extra_opts = xmalloc (strlen (opts) + 1); 
        **extra_opts = '\0';


 Hope this helps,


-- 
 Alain



