From: hm@seneca.ix.de (Harald Milz)
Subject: Re: 4 COM ports that share IRQ3,4
Date: Sun, 28 Nov 1993 12:05:10 GMT
Reply-To: hm@seneca.ix.de

Mark Buckaway (mark@datasoft.com) wroter

: >   The disadvantages:

: >   Electrically a bit hokey.  The 470 ohm resistor is on the small side,
: > [added note: my friend used 1K resistors with no problems]
: > but the drivers that are used for the interrupts are tanks and should be
: > able to provide sufficient source current.  You should use a germanium
: > diode for a low voltage drop.  I measured the drop of a bunch of small
: > signal diodes (silicon) out of my junk box and used the ones with the
: > smallest drop.

: >   DOS still won't work for two ports simultaneously (if you care :)
: > because the software drivers won't handle two-interrupts-at-once cases
: > right.

That's why I chose to wire COM3 and COM4 to IRQ 2 and 5, respectively.
 
Advantage: Win 3.1 allows for adjusting COM[3,4]IRQ and COM[3.4]ADDR,
thus you can use all 4 COM ports under Windows (if you care :). DOS will
not allow for those IRQs, though, without patching the COM3 and COM4 
device drivers. It was very cheap too because I can use a second
simple serial card for $10. Any other free interrupt will work equally
well but you should be aware which IRQs are used by other cards. 

Disadvantage: I will not be able to use LPT2 (which is wired to IRQ5
normally) ans IRQ2 (which is hardly ever used by other peripherals, even
not by VGA cards). Plus, you have to find the respective traces on the
PCB board, cut them with a knife and replace them by short pieces of
thin insulated wire. 

Ciao,
hm

